    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  COVID-19 poses a significant burden on populations worldwide. Although the pandemic has accelerated digital transformation, little is known about digitalization\u2019s influence on pandemic developments. Using the Digital Adoption Index (DAI), we examined the effects of digitalization on early COVID-19 cases, deaths, and stringency indices (SI) of government measures. Gradient Tree Boosting pinpointed essential features, such as populations\u2019 smoker fraction, age, poverty, and DAI. Then, regression analyses indicated that higher DAI was associated with significant declines in new cases (\u03b2=-362.25/pm;\n                  <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>\n                  &lt;0.001) and deaths (\u03b2=-5.53/pm;\n                  <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>\n                  &lt;0.001) months after the peak. Over the entire range, higher DAI was associated with higher mean SI (\u03b2=4.86;\n                  <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>\n                  &lt;0.01). Interestingly, however, in countries with high DAI &gt;0.68, the correlation inverted (\u03b2=-55.26;\n                  <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>\n                  &lt;0.05). Finally, a scoping review identified 70 publications providing valuable arguments for our findings. Thus, digitalization is evident for handling current and future pandemics but can also facilitate stronger government actions restricting individual freedom.\n                </jats:p>",
